AGI -&nbsp; Russian forces continue their advance through north-eastern Ukraine, conquering a series of small settlements along the border and forcing Ukrainian troops to withdraw from some positions. This, according to both Russian and Ukrainian military sources, is the situation in the conflict between Moscow and Kiev. The Russian Ministry of Defense has announced that its troops have occupied four other villages (Gatische, Krasnoye, Morokhovets and Oleinkovo) located north of Kharkiv, the second largest city in Ukraine, following the new offensive launched last Friday. The same Ukrainian armed forces admit that the Russian army is strongly advancing from the Russian-Ukrainian border to Kharkiv.
&nbsp;
"Today, during heavy fighting, our defenders were forced to withdraw from some other positions and another settlement passed completely under Russian control," said Hostri Kartuzy, a member of Ukrainian special forces in the late evening of yesterday.
&nbsp;
According to General Oleksandr Syrsky, military commander of the Ukrainian army, the situation in the Kharkiv region is "meaningly worsened" last week, although Russian attempts to break down Ukrainian defensive lines so far have not been successful. The Ukrainian troops, in numerical inferiority and without weapons, are already at the limit in an attempt to defend a front of 600 miles from the south of Kharkiv to the city of Kherson on the Black Sea. With the opening of a new northern front of Kharkiv, the Russian army aims to further stretch the Ukrainian lines and make it easier to break into some points, say the military experts cited by the New York Times.
&nbsp;
"The Russians have understood, just like many analysts, that the main disadvantage of which Ukraine is currently suffering is men," said Franz-Stefan Gady, a military analyst living in Vienna. "Using the first line, increase the likelihood of a turn." Gady and other experts said that the immediate goal of the new Russian offensive is to force the Ukrainian army to withdraw troops south of Kharkiv, especially around the merlate city of Chasiv Yar, a Ukrainian strategic stronghold in the south-east of the Donetsk region.
<br> Meanwhile,Moscow accused Ukraine of hitting a 10-story building in the Russian city of Belgorod, about 45 miles from Kharkiv. Vyacheslav Gladkov, governor of the Belgorod region, said that 19 people were injured in the bombing of the city and announced that two victims were extracted from the rubble.&nbsp;

